# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1902-philadelphia-athletics-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1901 Philadelphia Athletics season** involved the A's finishing fourth in the American League with a record of 74 wins and 62 losses.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The franchise that would become the modern Athletics originated in 1901 as a new franchise in the American League.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Western League had been renamed the American League in 1900 by league president Bancroft (Ban) Johnson, and declared itself the second major league in 1901.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1901, Johnson created new franchises in the east and eliminated some franchises in the west.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Philadelphia seems to have been a new franchise created to compete with the National League's Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Former catcher Connie Mack was recruited to manage the club.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Mack in turn persuaded Phillies minority owner Ben Shibe as well as others to invest in the team, which would be called the **Philadelphia Athletics**.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] He himself bought a 25 percent interest.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1901, Nap Lajoie jumped from the Phillies to the crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, owned by Connie Mack.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie's batting average that year was .426, still a league record.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The same year Lajoie became the second major leaguer to be intentionally walked with the bases loaded after Abner Dalrymple in 1881.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The 1902 Baltimore Orioles season finished with the Orioles in 8th place in the American League (AL) with a record of 50–88.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The team was managed by John McGraw and Wilbert Robinson.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The team played at Oriole Park in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] During the season, Andrew Freedman, principal owner of the National League's (NL) New York Giants, with the financial backing of John T.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush, principal owner of the NL's Cincinnati Reds, purchased the Orioles from John Mahon, who was deeply in debt.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] They raided the Orioles roster, releasing several of Baltimore's better players so that they could sign them to the Giants and Reds.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] AL president Ban Johnson seized control of the Orioles the next day and restocked their roster with players received on loan from other AL teams.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles' second season in Baltimore would ultimately prove to be their last, as after the season the team was replaced by the New York Highlanders, now known as the New York Yankees.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Knowing that placing a franchise in New York City was key to the success of the American League (AL), AL president Ban Johnson secretly met with principal owner John Mahon and player-manager John McGraw, who was also a part-owner, before the season about relocating to New York.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] However, the transfer did not occur when they could not find a suitable venue for the team.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In March, Mike Donlin went on a drinking binge in Baltimore, during which he was arrested for urinating in public and assaulting two chorus girls.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles released Donlin when he was sentenced to six months in prison.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Notable players jumped to the Orioles from the rival National League (NL).
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In December 1901, Joe Kelley jumped from the Brooklyn Superbas.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Later in the offseason, Jimmy Sheckard also jumped from Brooklyn.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kip Selbach and Jim Jackson jumped from the New York Giants, Ernie Courtney jumped from the Boston Beaneaters, Tom Hughes jumped from the Chicago Orphans, and Dan McGann jumped from the St.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles signed Bill Keister as a free agent.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] With these transactions, the Orioles were seen as a contender in the AL pennant going into the 1902 season.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles drew over 10,000 fans on Opening Day.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Three players returned to the NL in April 1902.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Jack Dunn and Steve Brodie jumped to the Giants in April.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Sheckard changed his mind about playing for the Orioles after four games, returning to Brooklyn.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Many Orioles found themselves suspended by Johnson by midseason, including McGraw and Kelley.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In early July, McGraw resigned from the team and signed with the New York Giants of the NL.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] At this point, the Orioles had a 26–31 record.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kelley and Wilbert Robinson succeeded McGraw as player-managers.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The franchise began to fall into significant debt by July.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kelley, son-in-law of part-owner John Mahon, reported that the team owed as much as $12,000 ($446,538 in current dollar terms).
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Unable to afford that debt, Mahon purchased shares of the team from Kelley and McGraw.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] With this, Mahon became the majority shareholder, owning 201 of the team's 400 shares.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] On July 17, 1902, Mahon sold his interest in the Orioles to Andrew Freedman, principal owner of the Giants, and John T.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush, principal owner of the Cincinnati Reds, also of the NL.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The transaction was reported to have been in the range of $20,000 ($744,231 in current dollar terms).
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] That day, Freedman and Brush released Kelley, Joe McGinnity, Roger Bresnahan, Jack Cronin, Cy Seymour, and Dan McGann from their Oriole contracts.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush then signed Kelley and Seymour to the Reds, while Freedman signed McGinnity, Bresnahan, Cronin, and McGann, joining McGraw, his new player-manager, on the Giants.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Though Kip Selbach and Jimmy Williams were both pressed to agree to relocate as well, they refused to leave Baltimore, saying they would honor their two-year contracts.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] McGinnity allegedly attempted to contact Johnson that night, offering to stay with the Orioles if he could receive Johnson's personal assurance that he was welcome to stay.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] McGinnity did not hear back from Johnson, who had left his phone off the hook that night to avoid being contacted, and joined his teammates with the Giants.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] On that day, the Orioles were forced to forfeit their game against the St.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Louis Browns, as Baltimore lacked the minimum number of players required to compete.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Johnson used a league rule to join the Orioles' minority owners to seize control of the team.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Now running the Orioles, Johnson sought to restock the team.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] He requested players from the other AL franchises to fill the Orioles' roster.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Sport McAllister was loaned to the Orioles from the Detroit Tigers for three games, but the Tigers requested McAllister back, as the Orioles came to Detroit to play the Tigers.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles received Pop Dillon from the Tigers, but released him after using him in two games.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Snake Wiltse was sent to the Orioles from the Philadelphia Athletics on July 19, but he struggled for the Orioles.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles also received Lew Drill on loan from the Washington Senators, sold Charlie Shields to the St.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Louis Browns and purchased Jack Thoney from the Cleveland Bronchos.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles finished the season with a 50–88 record, good for last place in the AL.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] For their final game at Oriole Park, the team drew only 138 fans.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] During the owners meetings in late 1902, the franchise was transferred to New York.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] MLB would not return to Baltimore until the former Browns moved to Baltimore in 1954.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The **1902 Boston Americans season** was the second season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished third in the American League (AL) with a record of 77 wins and 60 losses, 6+1⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans bolstered their pitching by recruiting Bill Dinneen, who jumped from the Boston Beaneaters.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Dinneen and Cy Young would become the "one-two" pitching combination for the Boston Americans.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Augusta, Georgia.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 11 home runs and had 121 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .342 batting average.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 45 appearances (43 starts) and pitched 41 complete games with a 32–11 record and 2.15 ERA, while striking out 160 in 384+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team had one game end in a tie; August 18 vs.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1902 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 32nd season of the franchise.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1902-philadelphia-athletics-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
